            <fr:title text="Reflection algebras and homomorphisms">Reflection algebras and homomorphisms</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {U}]]></fr:tex> be a subuniverse of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {V}]]></fr:tex> and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A:\mathcal {V}]]></fr:tex> be a type. A <html:em>reflection algebra</html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {U}]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[UX:\mathcal {U}]]></fr:tex> together with a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{A}\xrightarrow {{\eta _{X}}}{UX}]]></fr:tex>. A homomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> of reflection algebras from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is given by a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{UX}\xrightarrow {{Uf}}{UY}]]></fr:tex> together with a homotopy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\eta _{f} : {\eta _{Y}} \sim _{A\to  Y} {Uf\circ  \eta _X}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>When it causes no ambiguity, we will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X:\mathcal {U}]]></fr:tex> for the underlying type <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[UX]]></fr:tex> of a given reflection algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>; likewise, we will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f x]]></fr:tex> rather than <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Uf x]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
